Regarding the money for your tin, do not worry. I did not have the money sent to you with the travellers who were mugged. When the road opens, I will have it sent to you.
Concerning your copper, Adad-ṣulluli and I have sent for porters, but because glazed frost is on the roads, they just refused to go. I have just sent a message to Ili-wedaku for some donkeys; if he does not bring donkey(s) to me, (and) if my own donkeys have regained in strength, then I will load my own donkeys.
Today you wrote to me, saying: 'Why do you not open the road for me? I will open the road [from here]'.
There is turmoil in Purušhaddum. I can not enter entirely on my own. When the road reopens, I will enter without delay, and <gap>
Since there is truly a sikkātum and the roads are dangerous, I have not led (the shipment) to Hutka. When the road is free again, I will recompense you (pl.) with the first caravan.
Entrust all their textiles and the other's textiles to Ili-wedaku, so that he can pack them for (the) Durhumit road.
12 shekels to the Subarean for 4 wagonloads of wood.
