I gave half a mina and five shekels of tin and the trinkets to the king's counsellor
I paid one mina of tin in Badna to the house of Šu-Laban
Ten shekels of silver (were) for the wages for my three packers from Hahhum to Timelkiya
near to the Upper Lands
shekel of tin
Speak to Tuniya, my servant. Thus the Labarna, the Great King. You are my servant. Protect me, and I will protect you, my servant. Tikunan is my city and you are my servant, and your land is my land, and I will protect you. My campaign is ready, and the man of Hahhum has prepared his forces. Devour his provisions like a dog. The oxen you take will be yours. The sheep you take will also be yours. There will be two assaults against him: I from here, and you from there. Now send me the iron and the lion, which I heard that they have returned from Nihriya, and then, whatever you wish for, as much as you want, write to me and I will send it to you – silver, horses, prisoners and local slaves I will send. When I arrive at Zalpar, send my servant Bulli and your servant to me. If there are qani at hand, then send that to me. Also, have them bring white or black horsehairs to me. Also, do not listen to the lies he utters, but keep to the bull's horns, protect the tail of the lion, and do not hold on to the tail of the fox – the one who constantly produces lies. What I did to Zalpar, I will do to him. Do not ever listen to words on the right or left. Heed my words.
To Innaya
from Aššur-reṣi
You should not stay there
Go to Tegarama and stay in Tegarama
I paid three minas and five shekels of tin to the kaššum-official
1 1/2 mina and five shekels of tin for your envoy to Kaneš
I paid four shekels of silver for the hire of a donkey from Zalpa to Kaneš
When I went to Zalpa
My tablets are in Haqa. Dear fathers, let them pay the silver, seal it with your seals, and have it sent here. If there is no affiliated trader in the possession of a 'purse' going to Haqa, then make it (travel) safely to Šimala instead.
Three talents 28 minas (of tin) – the declared value of (the consignment belonging to) Ili-alum. Ten minas belonging to Amur-Aššur. Ten minas belonging to Iddin-Amurrum. In total three talents 48 minas. From the City to Apum 2 minas and 2 shekels per talent came on (as dātumšadduātum tax). Fifteen shekels was the headšadduātum tax. I paid 7 5/6 minas and 8 1/2 shekels. From Apum to Haqa its declared value was 3 talents and 40 minas. Two and a half minas and two shekels per talent came on (as dātumšadduātum tax). Five shekels each was the headšadduātum tax. I paid 9 1/3 minas and 2 shekels. From Haqa to Tegarama his shipment was three talents and 30 minas. At half a mina and 4 shekels per talent, I paid 1 5/6 mina and 6 shekels of tin. 6 shekels of tin was the transport cost for the outstanding claims in the City. 5/6 minas and 5 shekels in the mountains of Haqa. 1/3 mina and 5 shekels for sa'utum. 7 shekels for the Euphrates. 12 shekels were in deficit.
Puzur-Ištar said to Assur-taklaku: 'As for the fact that I hired you from Kaneš to Zalpa as well as Timelkiya – has your salary not been paid in full?'
Out of the 21 donkeys that I brought up on my journey, thereof one was led to Timelkiya by Aššur-šad-ili, two donkeys died in Zalpa, and I made 18 donkeys enter Kaneš.
When I myself left Timelkiya, I paid 15 shekels of silver for my inns. I went to them, to Zalpa, and I spent 5 shekels of silver.
If you go (to) Zalpa itself, then leave your textiles of good quality in the house of the gubabtum and state my name. If (you head) to Timelkiya, then leave them in the house of Adada in Šalahšuwa. Do not hand them over to a smuggler.
81[+x] kutānukutānum textiles are owed by Ikun-piya, son of Lulu. Select 40 textiles of extra high quality, and let them remain for Išme-Su'en in Zalpa, while he should bring in the rest of the textiles with him. Leave him one donkey.
At his departure, at the bank of the river in Zalpa
And on my way up from the City I will pay you the money
To my Lord from Yasim-sumu, your servant
I spoke to Aplahanda (king of Carchemish) in regard to Qaqqadanum's journey to Haššum
Abdi-erah was coming here from Zalba
I will fill your wine-boat, and I will also provide you with an escort, and then (you can) leave
His escort, a man from Zalba, stays in Carchemish
Wherever they are staying, your hand should seize them. If (they go) to Mamma, Ṣilla-Adad catch up with them. If (they go) to Zalpa or Tegarama, he should not tarry, but he should catch up with them.
I wrote to you earlier, saying: 'If your caravan is being packed, then you too should pack together with your caravan, and choose textiles of good quality from the goods of the merchant that you are carrying, and in Mamma or in Unapsesi the rest of the less good textiles – both from what remains of the merchant's and from your own working capital and from the working capital of the servants – should enter the palace together with your partners.' Now the winter has caught up with you in Uršu. Since there is a lot of snow, I have not sent anyone in whom I could trust to get the goods of the merchant
I have sent Uṣur-ša-Ištar to Enišarum concerning your tin. When they come back from Zalpa, I shall send Ali-ahum.
1/3 mina and 5 shekels of silver, the price of 10 slave-girls of Ašdu's, I paid to Kanuli in Uršu. I sold that one slave-girl to Amarum, son of Ibni-Adad, in Zalpa, and he led her to Aššur-taklaku, son of Ali-ahum, in Kaneš.
and I will complete the matter appropriately so that you go and provide textiles which you have left for me at Hattuš, textiles for copper<gap>
When you go to Zalpa, I will give you 10 minas of fine copper for that textile; the price of the copper will be determined by handshake
When Adad-bani and Šamaš-ublam entered Hanaknak, they seized them in the Office of the Colony. They confiscated the tablet from the Colony, which you gave to them, and on top of the 8 shekels of silver that they made them deposit, they have today drawn up their memoranda (acknowledging a debt) for 7 shekels per person. Adad-bani and Adad-ublam together said as follows: 'Ask the <gap> that we have not traded here – we have not traded in your country'. Because they maltreated them, they fled into the countryside. Here, the men who took the wool and promised to catch up with a caravan said: 'We will go on the journey'. But given that Adad-bani was not present, I confronted Ea-malik together with them, and I said: 'No matter what, they are not to go to the Land of Zalpa'. You should keep an eye on them there. They have promised me a trip to Kaneš. They are under no circumstances to go to the Land of Zalpa.
for an inn
to the palace
I left the goods in Tegarama and personally I went to Hattum. I myself carry the proceeds from Hattum.
Dear brothers, if it is possible for you there, dispatch the slave-girl and the children, as you are able. Make an arrangement of some 10 shekels of silver and have her brought to Tegarama or Hattum. If the guard posts are strong, and it is not feasible to set out, then measure out grain to (supply) her for one year. The servants should reach me in Luhuzattiya.
I am staying in Tegarama <gap> On the day you hear my letter, Ali-ahum should come and meet me in either Hurama or in Kuššara.
I paid 2 1/2 mina in sickles for an inn in Tegarama. 1/3 mina of sickles for wine in Talpa. I paid 15 shekels for an inn at the place where the servant died. 1/3 and 7 1/2 grains for wine in Supana. Half a shekel for the guards.
To the ten-man board of Tegarama from Anišu-kiba, the barullum-official in Tiburziya: Dear fathers and brothers
he should leave 45 pieces of garment<gap>
his agent was caught smuggling and Pušu-ken was jailed; a garrison was sent to Luhuzattiya, Hurama and Šalahšuwa in their lands, as the queen had instructed
he should saddle up the donkey belonging to Šukuku and Išme-Aššur
he is to hire porters, and not leave anything behind
he should let it travel to Luhuzattiya
when he enters Timelkiya he should send a message to you, and you should ask for a guide from Azu
then you must send him to Ali-abum
the Huramean and the Šalahšuwean should not levy the nishātumšadduātum tax
Five minas of scrap metal in the steppe for transport. From Qaṭṭara to Hamizanum 1/3 mina of tin for transport. I replaced a donkey and had to balance 1 mina and 15 shekels of tin. From Burallum to Birtu'um 17 shekels of tin for transport. 7 shekels of tin as hire of a wagon from 'the City of the Kanešeans' to Timelkiya. From Timelkiya to Hurma I paid 2 shekels of silver and 2 shekels of tin for the hire of a donkey. From Hura<ma> to Luhuzattiya I paid 3 shekels of silver and 3 shekels of tin for the hire of a donkey.
I paid half a shekel of silver for inns in Hurama. I paid Ikun-piya son of Daya 12 shekels in Luhuzattiya for the smuggling of the textiles. I paid 3 shekels of tin [for the donkey]s (and) his lodging [in GN]. I paid [x shekels of tin] at the bridge. I paid [x shekels of t]in for inns in Šamuha. I paid 1 shekel of silver in wages for the porter until Šamuha.
In total: 2 1/2 minas of silver was brought to you by Asanum. Sell the goods, be it in Luhuzattiya or in Šamuha.
From Man-mahir to Ali-ahum: Inform me whether or not they have brought in the textiles from Luhuzattiya. If they have brought them in, then convert them to silver as I instructed you <gap> Their smuggling (cost) 7 1/2 shekels of silver. They asked for 40 shekels of silver from Enna-Suen, but give them 7 1/2 shekels.
From Man-mahir to Ali-ahum: I have sent word to you both once and twice concerning the textiles that are in Luhuzattiya. If they have brought them in there (in Kaneš), then convert them to silver in accordance with my instructions.
On the day you hear my letter, Ali-ahum should come and meet me in either Hurama or in Kuššara
I will divide them in three, and let them travel to Tilimra, and then you can travel later yourself. Then they should let your slave-girl Silimma travel to Hurama, so you can come in here yourself.
You said: 'Within ten days, [I will send it to you] from either Kuššara or from Šamuha. If I do not [send it, I will pay you the] trip[le]'.
To Hanunu from Aššur-ṭab: The man of Kuššara has fallen upon us here in the Land of Zalpa together with the servants of Iddin-Su'en son of Kukulanum. [(detailed inventory of shipment)] all this, which <gap> went up to Kuššara, so I also personally went up (there), and I seized [<gap>] and the servant in the city gate, and I forced [<gap>] the Station, and made [<gap>] and the servant go up to the palace, and the marked bulls are standing (there). We went up to the palace several times, but the palace said: 'I took them as booty from the Land of Zalpa'.
I paid half a shekel of silver for inns in Hurama
I paid Ikun-piya son of Daya 12 shekels in Luhuzattiya for the smuggling of the textiles
I paid 3 shekels of tin [for the donkey]s (and) his lodging [in GN]
I paid [x shekels of tin] at the bridge
I paid [x shekels of t]in for inns in Šamuha
I paid 1 shekel of silver in wages for the porter until Šamuha
I paid 3 shekels of tin in Hatikaitra
I paid 1 1/2 mina of tin to the mayor in Kutiya
I paid 12 shekels of tin to the rabi sikkitim in Karahna
From Karahna to Kuburnat 3 shekels of silver came on (as expenses) for porters
I paid 6 shekels of silver as nishātumšadduātum tax at the border of [GN]
I paid 2 shekels for in[ns]
In total, Šalim-ahum must pay 3 minas 15 shekels of silver to Iddin-abum wherever he sees him upon his (return) up from the City, be it in Kaneš or in Hattum.
I hear that there is a market for kutānukutānum textiles in Kaneš. Make inquiries, and if you cannot make a profit in Kaneš then you must not release the kutānukutānum textiles on credit to a trader in Kaneš itself. Instead you must bring up my kutānukutānum textiles to either Hattum or to Purušhaddum.
(Do such and such), be it in Hattum or in Purušhaddum.
The king of Wašhaniya came here. He has prevented us from going to Purušhaddum or Hattum.
Your letter came, but you wrote nothing at all about the 4 shekels of tin that Dan-Aššur left behind in Kaneš. Why has he taken his weapons like a criminal and gone to Kunanamit? You wrote, saying: 'Because of him, I am barred from going to Hattum so he will enter Purušhaddum with me, and I will clear myself, and then I will send him to you as fast as possible'.
Puzur-Aššur took Ištar-Lamassi daughter of Aššur-nada as secondary wife, and he will take her with him wherever his travels lead him – to Hattum or to Purušhaddum – but he must return her with him to Kaneš. If he deserts her, he must pay 5 minas of silver.
He will not take a qadištu-wife in Kaneš or in Nihriya
