I left Timelkiya. Entrust and send the acorns that are available to him, including those belonging to the kaššum-official of Kupitta
From the midst of the mountains I paid ten shekels [of tin] each to get two side-packs to Hazu. From Lalga to Hazu I paid 7 1/2 shekel of t[in] for the two side-packs and one top-pack. From Hazu to Timelkiya I paid the two men 5 shekels of tin each. From Timelkiya to Hurama I have paid two shekels of silver and two shekels of tin. From Hurama to Kaneš: 6 shekels of silver for donkey-fodder.
It was not feasible to take the tin that Akiya brought onto the Narrow Track, and so we deposited it in Luhuzattiya. Send us a message whether we should let it enter Kaneš or not, and take a decision (about) where to (take) your tin.
Here Adada agreed with Aššur-ṭab son of Azuzaya in Šalahšuwa, and Adada has travelled to Kuššara to have the man swear an oath. He will get an oath from the man and then he will dispatch the goods of Azuzaya's son on the Narrow Track.
To Puzur-Aššur, say: Thus speaks Buzazu
tin together with copper
If it is feasible, I will let the tin enter the Narrow Track
let them make bundles and bring it into Kaneš in their lap
Out of 238 textiles of Iddin-Adad that entered the palace in Neša, 21 good textiles have gone off to Durhumit by the Narrow Track
Aššur-taklaku son of Kartaya leads 2 talents of tin and 11 textiles (on) one black donkey to you. He did not enter Kaneš, but from Zalpa he went (via) the Narrow Track
Thus says Ina-a, say to Aššur-ṭab and the king's commissioner: the ruler and the ruler's wife sent word to me about the Narrow Track. Thus they said: whoever possesses textiles and tin on the roads that I have seized, tin and textiles they should not carry off, and smuggle it away from me and send it on the Narrow Track road, they sent word to me, saying, 'Goods, tin and textiles, do not smuggle, and on the Narrow Track road anything do not send, lest you be sorry.' A very serious matter, do not send anything, lest you be sorry. Hear the letter carefully and send it to Aššur-ṭab.
to the City
your (pl.) messages are strict
a junior cannot enter
