I wrote to you, saying: 'Hire some porters (from Kaneš) to bring my tin to Nenašša'. I hear that they will not set travellers free to go to Wašhaniya. If my letter has reached you (concerning that) they have brought the Wahšušanean and the Kanišite an oath, then give (the tin) in a sikkum so that they can bring it.
If you are still in Kaneš, then travel to Wašhaniya, but do not enter until the Land settles down.
The three of us owe 100 textiles of good quality to the king of Wašhaniya. He owes us 4600 (minas) of copper and the proceeds on 10 minas of tin. In addition, he personally owes us the price of 100 textiles
To the envoys of the City and the Kaneš Colony from the Wahšušana Colony. The king of Wašhaniya has written to us, saying: 'I have seized the throne of my father. Let me swear an oath'.
town prefect
I met with the king in Ninašša, but he did not give me anything. He said: 'Come back from Ulama (first)'. He did not buy a single textile.
Thereupon, Aššur-ṭab travelled here from Ninašša, and he took the 4 talents of tin under the seal of Ali-ahum and their wrappings and brought (it) to Purušhaddum.
The plenary assembly of the Wahšušana Colony passed a verdict. In regard to the man, whom they sent to the river in Ninašša
Concerning the pirikannukutānum textiles belonging to you that Dudu gave me: I stood ready to go into Wahšušana, but there was too much mud, so I will turn back from the bank of River Zuliya and bring them to Ninašša.
To the Kaneš Colony from your envoys and the Wahšušana Colony. We have heard the tablets that the Stations of Ulama and Šalatuwar sent to us, we have sealed them, and now they are bringing them to you. The day we heard the tablets, we sent two messengers by the Ulama route and two messengers by the Šalatuwar route to Purušhaddum to clear the order.
The roads to Šalatuwar are not feasible, so I will turn around and go up to Ulama.
He packed the copper (to go) from Durhumit to Purušhaddum, and he packed his own donkey to (go) as far as Wahšušana, and then I led them (the remaining donkeys) out with the help of the guard-posts on the Ulama road and I returned.
