3 and 1/6 shekel of silver was the price of the cup and the inns
Speak to Tuniya, my servant. Thus the Labarna, the Great King. You are my servant. Protect me, and I will protect you, my servant. Tikunan is my city and you are my servant, and your land is my land, and I will protect you. My campaign is ready, and the man of Hahhum has prepared his forces. Devour his provisions like a dog. The oxen you take will be yours. The sheep you take will also be yours. There will be two assaults against him: I from here, and you from there. Now send me the iron and the lion, which I heard that they have returned from Nihriya, and then, whatever you wish for, as much as you want, write to me and I will send it to you – silver, horses, prisoners and local slaves I will send. When I arrive at Zalpar, send my servant Bulli and your servant to me. If there are qani at hand, then send that to me. Also, have them bring white or black horsehairs to me. Also, do not listen to the lies he utters, but keep to the bull's horns, protect the tail of the lion, and do not hold on to the tail of the fox – the one who constantly produces lies. What I did to Zalpar, I will do to him. Do not ever listen to words on the right or left. Heed my words.
To my Lord from Yasim-sumu, your servant. I spoke to Aplahanda (king of Carchemish) in regard to Qaqqadanum's journey to Haššum
I wrote to you earlier, saying: 'If your caravan is being packed, then you too should pack together with your caravan, and choose textiles of good quality from the goods of the merchant that you are carrying, and in Mamma or in Unapsesi the rest of the less good textiles – both from what remains of the merchant's and from your own working capital and from the working capital of the servants – should enter the palace together with your partners.'
Now the winter has caught up with you in Uršu. Since there is a lot of snow, I have not sent anyone in whom I could trust to get the goods of the merchant
I have sent Uṣur-ša-Ištar to Enišarum concerning your tin. When they come back from Zalpa, I shall send Ali-ahum.
I paid 2/3 shekels of silver for an inn in Mamma
I (or: he) declared 22 1/2 grains of silver in Tegarama when the textiles went up to the palace
I will personally send it to you (fem.) from either Mamma or from Tegarama
I paid 2 1/2 mina in sickles for an inn in Tegarama
1/3 mina of sickles for wine in Talpa
I paid 15 shekels for an inn at the place where the servant died
1/3 and 7 1/2 grains for wine in Supana
Half a shekel for the guards
To the ten-man board of Tegarama from Anišu-kiba, the barullum-official in Tiburziya
leave behind 45 garments of good quality of the cloaks of the feet of Amur-Ishtar, (and) 3 garments of Akidium in Hahhum
his smuggler, the son of Erra, who was with Pushukken, smuggled, and his smuggler was caught, and Pushukken was seized in the palace
you should ask for a guide from Azu
Five minas of scrap metal in the steppe for transport
From Qaṭṭara to Hamizanum 1/3 mina of tin for transport
