From Burallum to Birtu'um 17 shekels of tin for transport
7 shekels of tin as hire of a wagon from 'the City of the Kanešeans' to Timelkiya
From Timelkiya to Hurma I paid 2 shekels of silver and 2 shekels of tin for the hire of a donkey
From Hura<ma> to Luhuzattiya I paid 3 shekels of silver and 3 shekels of tin for the hire of a donkey
Your representatives gave me 7 talents and 20 minas of dirty wool in Luhuzattiya
1 talent 50 minas of ušītu-wool <gap> I took
300 kipunani and 100 combs, which your representatives gave me in Luhuzattiya
To Irma-Aššur from Ennam-Aššur
4 shekels of silver: inns; 1 1/2 shekels of silver for the kaššum-official in Hurama
5 shekels of silver for inns; 1 shekel of silver for the kaššum-official in Kuššara I gave to him as well
You said: divide them in three, and let them travel to Tilimra, and then you can travel later yourself. Then they should let your slave-girl Silimma travel to Hurama, so you can come in here yourself.
Thus (speaks) Šumi-abiya: Say to Aššur-bani and Aššur-ṭab
To our envoys and the Kaneš Colony from the Kuššara Station
Here we have heard that two Assyrians have been killed in the Land of Luhuzattiya
I paid 3 shekels of tin for the donkey(s) (and) his lodging
I paid 1 shekel of silver in wages for the porter until Šamuha
3 shekels of silver came on (as expenses) for porters
I paid 6 shekels of silver as nishātumšadduātum tax at the border
The king of Wašhaniya came here. He has prevented us from going to Purušhaddum or Hattum.
Your letter came, but you wrote nothing at all about the 4 shekels of tin that Dan-Aššur left behind in Kaneš. Why has he taken his weapons like a criminal and gone to Kunana-mit? You wrote, saying: 'Because of him, I am barred from going to Hattum so he will enter Purušhaddum with me, and I will clear myself, and then I will send him to you as fast as possible'.
the purchase of the <gap> that they know about, send me some money to the libbi mātim of Hattum so that I can make the purchases
