from Kaneš to the city for provisions I paid
Four textiles belonging to Hanu son of Itur-ili, which Damqani brought from Hahhum to Timelkiya and entrusted to Iddin-Su'en in Timelkiya
Four porters from Timelkiya to Hurama at 26 shekels per person: I paid 1 mina 44 shekels
100 kutānukutānum textiles, 4 talents of tin and its extras (on) 5 donkeys, which Šu-Belum and Itur-ili checked in Timelkiya and in [GN], I paid 2 minas 10 shekels of silver for the transport of the tin and the textiles from Hahhum to Hurama. 1 mina of silver was spent on the messengers that I kept sending to Hahhum for the goods
I paid 2 shekels of silver and 2 shekels of tin from Timelkiya because a donkey suffered a stroke. I paid six shekels of silver and six shekels of tin from Hurama to Kaneš
If they demand good textiles from you for sale, be it Kuburnat, in Hanaknak, or in Durhumit, then you should sell the good textiles for cash on delivery for half a mina a piece. Do not set (them) free for sale on credit
2 talents of tin, 4 textiles of good quality and 3 textiles of ordinary quality and a black donkey that Pilah-Ištar will lead down from Hahhum: if there is (a price of) 8 shekels of tin per shekel of silver, then sell the tin and send your message to me here
If there is not (a price of) 8 shekels of silver per (mina to be had), then do not sell it for silver. Do not let them send the tin via Šalahšuwa
For the safety of my tin, they should let the tin travel via Timelkiya to Durhumit
In regard to the Narrow Track that you wrote to me about saying: 'For the safety of my money, you should do (your best) to save every shekel of silver and headšadduātum tax'. When the Narrow Track opens we will do as (instructed) in your message
