Speak to Imdilum, thus (say) Amur-Istar and Uzua: the merchandise entered the palace and the palace bought 17 m.kutānum textiles of Puzur-Assur and 3 of your's at 20 minas (of copper) each. (For a value of) 220 minas of refined copper the palace bought (wool) at a rate of 1:2, and (it was agreed that) we collect the copper in the kârum-office. On this very day the palace has satisfied us with the copper as payment for the textiles, and with the fine copper, but it did not give us anything for those of the bulk (of the merchandise). Don't worry! As many textiles as possible have been sold. We will sell both tin and copper and obtain silver, about 10 minas, and send Adu (with the silver) with the next caravan.
I hear that Amur-ili has sold piecemeal tin and textiles for copper in Wahsusana. My dear brothers, Amur-ili must not go (a second time) to Wahsusana!! He should bring all my merchandise into Purushattum and sell it for cash.
Thus (says) Amur-Istar, speak to Imdilum: You entrusted me with the caravan to Hurasanum and brought me the tablet. In my tablet I have listed all the debts you have with me in the kârum. Only 1 mina (is missing) from you, just as Uzua mentioned to me. Thus (I say): Before I depart, the wool should be converted to copper and the maidservant of Uzua should be exchanged for fine copper. For 60 talents of wool, either with a merchant or with the caravan driver, we agreed and the profit (was) 40 talents. When it arrived, it was checked. The remainder of the wool is still in Tigmurna.
