May he anoint with oil my monumental inscriptions, make sacrifices, (and) return (them) to their places
At the beginning of my sovereignty (lit. at the beginning of the throne of my sovereignty) I uprooted 28,800 Hittite people
from Syria (lit. 'Beyond the Euphrates') and led (them) into my land
the lands Madani, the land Nihani, the land Alaia, the land<gap>
the land Purulmezi and the territory of the land Subari
I cut straight as a string (and) subdued forty kings and their troops at my feet
At that time I approached Kaštilaašu, king of Kardunias, to do battle
I brought about the defeat of his army. In the midst of that battle I captured Kaštilaašu, king of the Kassites
I bound and brought him as a captive into the presence of the god Aššur, my lord
I became lord of Sumer and Akkad in its entirety (and) stood over them (its inhabitants) with joy and excellence
At that time the god Aššur, my lord, requested of me a cult centre on the bank opposite my city, the desired object of the gods, and he commanded me to build his sanctuary
At the command of the god Assur, the god who loves me, I built before my city, Assur, a city for (the god) Aššur on the opposite bank, beside the Tigris, in uncultivated plains (and) meadows
where there was neither house nor dwelling, where no ruin hills or rubble had accumulated, and no bricks had been laid
I called it Kār-Tukultī-Ninurta
I cut straight as a string through rocky terrain
I cut a wide path for a stream which supports life in the land (and) which provides abundance, and I transformed the plains of my city into irrigated fields
I arranged for regular offerings to Aššur and the great gods, my lords, in perpetuity
